{
  "card_id": "open_high_low_close",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Open High Low Close",
  "aliases": [
    "candlestick ohlc structure",
    "candlestick OHLC structure",
    "ohlc",
    "OHLC",
    "OHLC candle formation",
    "ohlc candle formation",
    "OHLC setup",
    "ohlc setup",
    "OLHC",
    "Open Low High Close"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "Open High Low Close (OHLC) refers to the four price points of a candlestick: open, high, low, close. The order these extremes form defines intraday delivery sequence: OHLC signals bearish delivery (high first, then low, close low); OLHC signals bullish (low first, then high, close high). Relative positioning of open and close with wicks classifies candles as directional, reversal, or indecision.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Open is the first traded price of the candle's time period; mark it as a horizontal reference level.",
    "High is the highest price reached during the candle's time period, including wicks.",
    "Low is the lowest price reached during the candle's time period, including wicks.",
    "Close is the last traded price of the candle's time period; the relationship between Open and Close determines whether the candle is bullish (Close > Open) or bearish (Close < Open).",
    "An indecision candle is identified when Open and Close are at relatively the same price level, producing a small body with wicks extending in both directions, regardless of how wide the High-to-Low range is.",
    "A directional candle is identified when Close is significantly above (bullish) or below (bearish) the Open, with the body occupying a large portion of the High-to-Low range.",
    "A reversal candle has a large wick relative to its body; price initially moves in one direction then reverses to close near the opposite extreme.",
    "Bearish OHLC sequence: price opens, forms the high first (often via a liquidity sweep), then trades lower to close near the low. Bullish OLHC: opens, forms low first (liquidity sweep), then rallies to close near the high.",
    "Higher time frame bias: if the prior HTF candle swept a high and closed back inside its range, anticipate OHLC; if swept a low and closed inside, anticipate OLHC.",
    "Confirm the sequence on a lower time frame with a change in state of delivery (close through opposing swing candles) and/or an opposing run that validates the wick (e.g., 08:30/09:30 EST for daily).",
    "Anchor the daily candle to the 00:00 EST open, and the 4-hour candles to 10:00 and 14:00 EST opens, mapping the OHLC/OLHC sequence accordingly.",
    "The extreme that forms first (high in OHLC or low in OLHC) should ideally reach the lower/upper half or mean threshold of the opposing higher-timeframe candle.",
    "Map lower-timeframe session highs and lows (Asia, London, New York) to identify which session formed the candle's high and low.",
    "Compare daily close to daily open: if close ≈ open, the day is range-bound; if significantly different, direction was delivered.",
    "Prerequisite for ICT-specific OHLC: higher time frame has formed a change in state of delivery (CSD), confirming reversal bias.",
    "Target candle open should be within the prior candle's range.",
    "Target candle sweeps the left swing high or HTF wick.",
    "Target candle closes below its open, forming an opposing candle."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "OHLC analysis classifies candles as directional, reversal, or indecision to guide bias. When HTF sweep and range closure anticipate an OHLC (bearish) or OLHC (bullish) sequence, traders wait for the manipulation wick to form (liquidity sweep), confirmed by a change in state of delivery, then enter in the body's direction targeting prior swing points. Fractal application around anchored opens (midnight, 10:00, 14:00) yields precise entries with stops beyond the wick. Avoid expansion trades during indecision; after three consecutive same-type candles, anticipate a reversal or consolidation.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Attempting expansion trades on a day forming an indecision candle, when price repeatedly returns into the range.",
    "Ignoring the relationship between the daily open and close, treating a small candle closing near the open as meaningful directional delivery.",
    "Trading the OHLC sequence without first aligning with the higher time frame bias (e.g., prior HTF candle must sweep and close back inside its range; expecting bullish OLHC while price is in premium is misaligned).",
    "Entering before a change in state of delivery confirms the swing point, as no reversal occurs without a swing point.",
    "Anticipating expansion before the manipulation wick is fully formed, neglecting the opposing run (e.g., 08:30/09:30) that validates the high/low.",
    "Confusing 4-hour OHLC anchor times across asset classes (e.g., Forex uses different 4-hour opens than indices, not the 09:30 NYSE open).",
    "Assuming a series of directional candles will continue indefinitely; typically after three consecutive directional candles, a reversal or consolidation is likely.",
    "Not confirming higher time frame change in state of delivery before trading ICT-specific OHLC, leading to false signals.",
    "Treating any opposing candle as an OHLC pattern without the prerequisite bias confirmation.",
    "Entering before the full OHLC candle formation is complete."
  ],
